You’re right that none of those are a clean mirror opposite.

“Suicide” is a very specific act: intentionally ending one’s own life.
So the true logical opposite would be something like:

intentionally continuing or creating one’s own life.

There isn’t a perfect single English word for that, which is why the suggestions felt a little off.

A few concepts that come closer depending on how you look at it:
	•	Self-creation — choosing to construct or remake your life
	•	Self-renewal — deliberately starting again
	•	Rebirth — symbolic or literal beginning of a new life
	•	Natality — a philosophical term (used by Hannah Arendt) meaning the human capacity to begin something new

Philosophically, many thinkers treat the opposite of suicide not as mere survival but as the decision to keep participating in life and possibility.

So if suicide is:

choosing to end your story,

the closest conceptual opposite might be:

choosing to begin or continue writing it.

If you want, we can also look at this from a linguistic or philosophical angle—there’s a really interesting reason English doesn’t have a clean opposite word here.